result.execSummary:
The defendant Printis E Smith was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Carry Concealed Weapon, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 941.23(2).
  • Resisting or Obstructing an Officer, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 946.41(1).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt:
Sentencing hearing proceeded. Statements by State, Defense Counsel, and Defendant.

AS TO COUNTS 1 AND 2:
Court ordered Defendant to serve 120 DAYS in the House of Correction with credit for 1 DAY time served. Huber privileges to apply for work and school.

Court STAYED the sentence and placed defendant on PROBATION for 12 MONTHS.

CONDITIONS OF PROBATION
-No violations of State or Federal law that rise to the level of probable cause.
-Complete 20 hours of community service.
-No use or possession of dangerous weapons or firearms except for the sole purpose of completing a firearm safety course.
-Complete a firearm safety course.
-Maintain full-time employment, school, or combination of both.
-Pay ALL MANDATORY costs, fees, and surcharges during the term of probation. Failure to pay will result in a civil judgment.
-Court waived all NON-MANDATORY costs, fees, and surcharges.
-Restitution set at zero.
-Defendant is to provide a DNA sample and pay the DNA surcharge.
-Upon successful completion of the sentence Court will allow for expungement.

APPELLATE RIGHTS GIVEN

Defendant Printis E Smith in court.  Attorney Corey R. Flynn in court for Printis E Smith.  Prosecuting attorney Navjot Singh Hira in court for the State of Wisconsin. 
Case spun from Branch 30. Case in court for Plea and Sentencing Hearing.  State advised the Court they have complied with the Victims' Rights Law. 
Parties have reached a resolution. State placed negotiations on the record. Defense counsel and defendant confirms. 
Court is in receipt of the; Plea Questionnaire, Addendum and WIS JI- Criminal/Elements of the Offense.

AS TO COUNTS 1 AND 2:

PLEA HEARING HELD:  Defendant changes his plea to GUILTY.  Defendant examined as to his plea, advised of his Constitutional rights and the maximum penalty.  
Defendant advised that if he is not a United States Citizen, deportation is possible. Court found that defendant knowingly, voluntarily and intelligently waived his rights. 
Parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis to sustain defendant's plea. State consents to the Jury Waiver. Court found defendant guilty and ordered a Judgment of Conviction be entered on the record. 
Court ordered a DNA sample and advised defendant of applicable surcharge. 

Sentencing to proceed.
